<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by OEx Ltd (HOT0069)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">OEx</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Ltd (HOT0069)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Standard Assessment Procedure</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Using SAP is rather like driving a Model T Ford to work every day. Some improvements have been made along the way to parts of it, but the underlying structure is old, outmoded technology.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The original endeavour with SAP, in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 1993, was to produce a simple compliance calculation, that could be completed by ‘the average builder’ ; filling in boxes and performing simple arithmetical calculations on paper.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although SAP has evolved further, and shifted onto the computer, it still </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uses the same very basic physical model to produce an approximate, standardised annual building energy cost.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">20 years on, the world has changed. Widespread internet access means that ‘the average builder’ is able to easily access sophisticated computer sy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stems and software. The current SAP could easily be replaced with a far more sophisticated and accurate building energy calculation methodology.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SAP was not meant to be used as a design tool, only as a simple compliance tool, so one might argue that SAP’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inaccuracy is less important. But in practice the need to ultimately comply using SAP means that building design decisions are commonly made on the basis of a SAP calculation i.e. on the basis of inaccurate and possibly misleading information. It is this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issue which led us, as designers and researchers of low carbon buildings, to abandon the use of SAP entirely, nearly 10 years ago.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The obvious implication of using an inaccurate calculation methodology to design new buildings or improve existing buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, is that buildings don’t perform as expected. The negative perception that results from false expectations undermines positive steps to improve the energy performance of buildings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our own comparison of the world’s calculation methodologies identified th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e German standard DIN18599 as the best balance of accuracy of output for simplicity of input. We adopted and developed this methodology. The kernel or calculation engine behind the Standard is very precisely engineered and robust (in the German fashion), a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd this is why it works so well for a wide range of building types, and for improvements to old inefficient buildings as well as for new zero carbon buildings. We recognised that the underlying sophistication of the methodology was an essential building bl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ock to allow a flexible (more British!) approach to cost effective emissions reductions. The effect of any proposed measure can be modelled in advance to a high degree of accuracy. We added the ability to use weather data from any UK weather station, or an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y global weather station for that matter. The kernel can be linked to local databases of construction components and templates for local building types. The Standard, and the algorithm behind it, were developed by the Fraunhofer Institute in Germany. The F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raunhofer used their work on the DIN18599 Standard to develop the EU’s own calculation tool under EN 15603 for the EPBD Recast, to compare Member State’s calculation methodologies, and thus DIN18599 became the first methodology to comply with EN15603 for b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oth new and existing buildings, and for all building types.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our OEx methodology is a full simulation, and it allows assessment of all types of energy flows for the intended heating, cooling, domestic hot water, ventilation, lighting and appliances of buil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dings. The calculation is crucially taking into account the effects of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">interaction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of energy flows between the elements of building structure and building systems.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have attached the specification separately, but to broadly outline the main differenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es between SAP and OEx(18599):</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OEx uses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">hourly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> weather data (typically 10 year average measurements for temperature, humidity, solar radiation, wind speed and wind direction from Meteonorm) to calculate heating and cooling demand, lighting usage, hot wate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r energy demand, renewable energy generation and ventilation for a specific location (weather station). All these aspects of energy use are connected within the calculation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SAP uses a simple degree day basis to calculate monthly heating demand; number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">days where heating is required - there is now some provision for regional variation in the UK.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Solar input to renewable energy technologies are notional averages for generic technologies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lighting use is a simplified calculation with an allowance for avera</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ge daylight.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SAP is a series of unconnected, simplified calculations for each aspect of energy use, which are then totalled.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">[The OEx methodology was used to model improvements to All Souls College, Oxford. One result of the study was that changing the anc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ient lighting system to a new energy efficient system would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">increase</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the energy demand of the building. This result came about because the resistance heating effect of the incandescent lighting was more efficient than the antiquated heating system. Of cour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se it points to the replacement of both the heating and lighting systems, but it illustrates the importance of an holistic calculation methodology, such as DIN18599. SAP would give the opposite result – a reduction in energy demand with low energy lighting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">].</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OEx requires a user pattern to be defined, and this is applied to the simulation. The user pattern is flexible within certain limits.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SAP has a fixed ‘inherent’ user pattern (it ignores user intervention and assumes the building is heated regardless of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">occupancy). Inaccuracies of more than 100% between calculated and actual energy demand are not uncommon due to the fixed user pattern in SAP and other BREDEM based models. And this has led to many wrong decisions, for example, even on the relatively simple</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> matter of the cost effectiveness of extra insulation (in broad terms, if a building is actually heated for twice as long as modelled, the real payback period for extra insulation is halved).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OEx requires zones to be defined – that is; areas of a building </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which are used differently to others in energy terms. The use of zones in simulations provides considerable improvements in accuracy of the calculation of energy performance. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SAP does not accommodate the input of zones.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OEx has always calculated outputs o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f CO2, CO, NOX, CXHY, and SO2 for different fuel sources. One of the outputs of the calculation is the annual CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e (CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> equivalent) emissions for the subject building.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SAP has not previously taken account of greenhouse gasses other than CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, although this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aspect is beginning to be improved in SAP2012. For example, comparing biomass and photovoltaic alternatives to provide space heating and hot water for low carbon homes will produce opposite (wrong) results for emissions in SAP, compared to more accurate me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thodologies. The Nitrous Oxide produced by biomass has a greenhouse gas equivalence of 298x, which, if ignored, can significantly change the results. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This last point about greenhouse gasses illustrates the essential need for accuracy in calculation metho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dology. Increasing greenhouse gas emissions when you think you are reducing them cannot </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be a desirable course. And this is one of the significant reasons why we abandoned SAP as a methodology.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have talked a little about our experiences, and our endeavou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs to produce cost effective emissions reductions from buildings, but we are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> making the general point that a much more reliable methodology than SAP is readily available in our current state of technological evolution, particularly with respect to advances i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n computing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no need to rely on a ‘series of simple equations’ when a computer system will, behind the scenes, calculate the holistic performance of a complex building system and its users, on an hourly basis, through a typical year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The inputs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">required through the user interface of a new methodology could be made be less complex and less time consuming than those currently required by SAP. And the technology readily exists to predetermine how input parameters could be limited to meet regulatory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requirements. Sound guidance for reducing emissions could be provided to users</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is easily feasible to have a regulatory compliance tool which is also a reliable design tool. And this is what we all need to meet 2050 targets.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>